  "title": "Epilog 1994",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "07887497f097f327",
      "text": "When a book is reprinted unchanged thirty years after its first publication, this is likely to be an occasion to re-contextualize the text. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ece9d4143d546d83",
      "text": "This is especially true in a field that can be broadly described as empirical organization science, to include not only sociological organization research, but also social psychological and, in the broadest sense, \"behaviorist\" approaches of political, or economic, provenance. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1ef012a5c88a1d7b",
      "text": "Undoubtedly, much has changed in this rapidly evolving field in thirty years. Even if one disregards the ongoing change of self-recommendation fashions in the management consulting literature, organizational science today is not the same as it was in 1964. But this need not mean that certain research perspectives have been refuted or otherwise rendered obsolete. For the most part, sciences do not develop according to the scientific-theoretical model of asserting, testing, and accepting or rejecting hypotheses. This would result in no history at all, but only a waste mountain of discarded attempts at knowledge. Rather, it seems to be the case that one works for a while with certain distinctions in order to work out what can be made visible with them, and when this begins to bore after some time, one moves on to other distinctions."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "762ef961d2ca9797",
      "text": "Reproducing the distinctions with which organizational research has worked or is still working is one way of refreshing its memory. Often it remains relatively unclear from what a preferred view is distinguished. This is very typically true of models that make rationality recommendations. But as soon as one asks the memory of the system to reconstruct the distinctions of the preceding tradition and to mark them as distinctions, it becomes better understood that progress - if progress it is - takes place through a change in the forms of distinction with which work is done; and neither through a refutation of hypotheses nor through a more or less arbitrary shift of thematic interest. But if this is so: which distinctions were and are important for [[ Funktionen und Folgen formaler Organisation]] (Functions and Consequences of Formal Organization), which distinction policy was the leitmotif then, and what has changed since then?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ace5e04ac90a20f3",
      "text": "It was not about [[Max Weber]]'s bureaucratic model. It was not about the idea that organization is a rationally conceived ap paratus of rule, the functioning of which could then, on unbiased observation, trigger astonishment mixed with astonishment. It was not at all about the difference between ideal type and deviation, which at that time, especially in the USA, was often misunderstood and subjected to empirical tests. Rather, important suggestions from the American sociology of organization were taken up. However, their guiding distinction was at that time the distinction between formal and informal organization."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8f52966316173254",
      "text": "The American discussion, to which one could look back at the beginning of the 1960s, had enriched the schema formal / informal organization with certain added options, but also burdened it. Informal organization was mainly understood in terms of group psychology, i.e., as the spontaneous self-development of groups. This corresponded to widespread research interests in social psychology at that time. Furthermore, groups as bearers of informal organization had been observed and researched from the management's point of view. This brought into play another distinction that was only meaningful from this perspective, namely that of underperformance and overperformance. On the one hand, groups had to be expected to slow down performance to a level acceptable to them and to cooperate in covering up poor performance or mistakes; but on the other hand, given a good group climate, it was also possible to think in terms of additional performance, which could not have been ordered. Thus, one could hope and expect from the side of the researchers that the knowledge of the mechanisms of informal organization could be of help to the management in understanding the processes in the company and in the daily business of the management. Finally, since the famous Hawthorne experiments, the relevant research had taken place mainly in organizations of industrial production. There, groups were easy to discover because of the formal organization of work and their spatial (machine-related) coherence. But this also spared the question whether the extent to which formal organization leads to the formation of informal groups does not vary from type of organization to type of organization, so that the findings on informal organization can only be generalized to a very limited extent. During many years of work in public administration, [[Niklas Luhmann]] had encountered [[Coalition]]s and [[Network]]s of various kinds, but not groups in a sense that could be delimited on the basis of their self-understanding."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b28f0b77b204b4e8",
      "text": "This was also a motive not to give up the insights into a difference between formal and informal organization, but to complement and relativize them by another distinction, and for this, based on the state of research at that time, above all the distinction between system and environment came into consideration. Roughly speaking, it offered the possibility of tracing the difference between formal and informal organization back to the differentiation of a social system \"organization\"; for one could imagine that the difference thus created imposed problems on the differentiated system which could not be solved by the means of formal organization alone, i.e. not by a departmental division and a hierarchy which concentrated external contacts (or at least: their regulation) at the top of the system if possible. Above all, the concrete work motivation of the members, but also the inconspicuous and relatively smooth solution of the problems, which today [[Transaction Cost Analysis]] discusses, can hardly be sufficiently guaranteed by formal regulations. "
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "69e9496f9a254070",
      "text": "~"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0928708a76806bb2",
      "text": "This following Ronald Chose, The Nature of the Firm (1937), quoted from the imprint in The Firm, the Market, and the Law, Chicago 1988, p. 33-55; but especially since Oliver E. Williamson, Markets and Hierarchies: Analysis and Antitrust Implications: A Study in the Economics of Internal Organisation, New York 1975."
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "d973b982ddeb4cad",
      "text": "~",
      "alias": "69e9496f9a254070"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "13885d73db3f55db",
      "text": "Thus it could be thought that the difference of formal and informal organization, or now better: formal and informal communication, is used as a kind of catching difference for environmental complexity and makes it possible, depending on the of the problems, solutions can be sought partly in a formal and partly in an informal way."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "350e8901dd10b140",
      "text": "The combination of both distinctions, system/environment and formal/informal, could be achieved by the term \"membership role\" („Mitgliedschaftsrolle“). Consequently, it forms the central category of the preceding text. For only communications that the members of the organization engage in their role as members are attributed to the organization. Everything else, buildings, machines, but also the people themselves and all that non-members negotiate among themselves, belongs to the environment of the system. Moreover, it is clear that membership is assumed by decisions and terminated by decisions. Thus, it is decisions by which the organization generates itself and demarcates itself from its environment in ongoing communication. Finally, the notion of role was meant to express that while roles establish membership in the organization and certain general expectations, the violation of which will lead to loss of membership in the long run, this still leaves much room for maneuver that can be filled by both formal and informal communication."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a3baa5a1265c61b4",
      "text": "Systems theory at that time was admittedly not yet in the form that could be observed twenty years later. Although the relationship between cybernetics and self-reference had already been lively discussed in the large Macy conferences of the 1950s, and although \"self-organization\" was an established topic around 1960, the export of systems theory to disciplines outside the core group was still based on relatively simple models – above all the stabilization model of negative feedback or homeostasis and the input/output model, which treated the transformation of inputs into outputs as a matter of a simple mathematical calculus or an appropriately constructed machine. The fact that this could not work for mathematical reasons as soon as outputs were reintroduced into the system as inputs, i.e. reflexive loops were formed, only became known later in wider circles."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0d498c2bd01cd3dd",
      "text": "Until well into the 1970s, therefore, systems theory was reproached for treating human things in the manner of machines and thus for placing them \"conservatively\" in the service of ruling classes. On the part of systems theory, there was at first only an attempt to provide within this theory for soothing distinctions, such as that of artificial and natural or that of mechanical and organic models, but the counter-models remained unclear and functioned only as placeholders for a complexity that could not yet be scientifically grasped. On these bases, the controversy could only be fought out ideologically, and eventually, after both sides had made their scent marks, lost its intellectual appeal. But this without the newer approaches to a theory of self-referential systems having been considered, let alone tried out as a theory of organization."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "11ac19e89ce585a5",
      "text": "In contrast, the view has become established, also and especially in organizational research, that systems cannot be regarded as artificial or natural wholes, but that the difference between system and environment must be assumed. In this sense, systems theory established the system/environment distinction as the guiding concept of organizational sociology. At first, the environment was treated as a turbulent, overly complex external world on which the organization was dependent, be it in its information, be it in its resources. The information/resource distinction, in turn, led to a bifurcation that brought into view either problems of uncertainty or problems of power in the sense of resource control. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "640435485bf5cc18",
      "text": "This so-called contingency theory was in turn criticized at the end of the 1970s with the accusation that it saw the environment of organizations as too unstructured, whereas in reality it was always a question of society, which had accepted certain cultural patterns and values and had thus always already limited its own complexity. So now the distinction system environment / society came into view, and contingency theory was supplemented by institutional theory, if not displaced from the prominent places of theory development. This corresponded to a conviction, spreading especially in business enterprises, that a company could not legitimize itself socially solely through its product, but that social factors and, most recently, ecological consequential problems of its production processes also played a role. For public administration, this corresponds to the insight that successful activity, especially in view of the expansion of tasks in the wake of the welfare state, cannot be legally enforced in many cases, but is dependent on the cooperation of those concerned. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a935fdd5b10aba30",
      "text": "Of course, the old concept of [[Institution]] can reflect this only very inadequately; but it at least responds to expanded conditions of acceptance of organizations in the society surrounding them. In these distinctions linked to distinctions, the insight gains of the old distinction of formal and informal organizations get out of sight without having been refuted or even devalued in any way. It is just that the spotlights of current interest tend to illuminate other areas, more the external relations of organizations."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9163d75e2d228acc",
      "text": "One must therefore describe \"the environment\" of the organization more precisely than the older contingency theory had done. Today, however, this is no longer done only by means of the distinction between environment and society with its correlate concepts of institution and culture. Recently, it has also been done by the so-called network analyses. Here the system / environment distinction is supplemented or, as the protagonists think, replaced by a plethora of system-to-system distinctions. It can be clearly seen that here further arguments against the classical model of hierarchical-centralized management are being raised. In the network, non-centralized information accrues, because here effects of changes can and must be assessed – effects on trust, limits of reasonableness, resilience, surviving gains and losses in a relationship; and in the realm of state and community organizations, for example: consequences of political changes. Above all, it seems to be accelerations and increases in the impact of structural changes that draw attention to this phenomenon. After all, there have always been weighty customer and supplier dependencies or dependencies on public financial sources or on political conspicuousness / inconspicuousness. The new topics of observation do not go beyond the framework of systems theory; and especially when central planning becomes more difficult, one must at least be able to determine whether one has to reckon with internal or external conditions and proceed accordingly in the organization or as in the market."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "54f68c21e8e3f55b",
      "text": "However, it might become more difficult to still believe in the rationality of decisions under the conditions which are preferably of interest today, and thus we come across another theory development which has been influential especially since the 1970s. It lives from its opposition to the classical doctrine of optimal rationality, which for its part was based on the distinction between ends and means. The big names here are James March and Karl Weick. At the time of the publication of Functions and Consequences of Formal Organization, the trend was already visible, but had not attracted interest either in business administration (the exception being Horst AIbach) or in the sociology of organization. Herbert A. Simon had emphasized the limits of the information processing possibilities demanded by the principle of optimization, and had changed the theory of rational decision from an orientation towards the sole deciding entrepreneur to a theory of decisions of elaborating organizations. Following Simon, one already spoke of \"bounded rationality\". A two-stage model had been introduced, which worked with the assumption of decisions about decision premises. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ae47e09d0235464f",
      "text": "[[Niklas Luhmman]] was able to link to this state of affairs – especially with the thesis that the hiring and firing of members fixes, bundles and changes decision premises of the system. With this summary, it was possible to integrate systems theory, decision theory, and the theory of formal and informal organizations. A very consequential and successful book by Cyert and March on a behavioral theory of organizations had just been published. Nevertheless, the scope of this movement could not yet be estimated. Their concern was and is, as can be seen today, not only a critique of exaggerated rationality claims – as if management had to be brought back to the ground of empirical reality. Right down to the style of language, it is about the astonishment that it also works without rationality – and how it works."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ddfed6edc7a218e5",
      "text": "But if this is the guiding difference, namely rationalistic self-descriptions and behavioral presumptions on the one hand and the successfully ignoring reality on the other hand: how should a theory of organization encompassing both be formulated? The next generation of researchers is making further distinctions here – for example, Nils Brunsson's distinction between \"talk\" and \"action\". This amounts to the distinction between ideas and motives. But it is hard to see – and this applies to all distinctions! – how one could have one side without the other."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "590484d1c06013da",
      "text": "When you tell history on the basis of distinctions, you don't tell it as it was meant to be told. Scientific discoveries become unilaterally flagged, for example, as informal organization or not-so-rational decision-making. Reconstructing distinctions neutralizes, in a sense, the joys of discovery and the punctuations at which discontinuities make themselves felt. One must abandon the hope of telling the history of science according to the \"A causes B\" causal model. Rather, it is a history of continuous discontinuity, a history of \"reaction to ...,\" a self-motivating history. But if one wants to tell history not as a history of facts, but as a history of observations, it must be noted that any designation of something thereby determined requires the distinction from something else - first, of course, the distinction from \"everything else,\" especially in the history of science, but also the distinction from the hitherto usual."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "efc1d2df92f10092",
      "text": "One does not have to describe such a zigzag course, which always swings the respective used distinctions along, as progress, as if nothing would be lost. Rather, an evolutionary theory applies to the situation, which reckons with the fact that in the course of time the complexity to be mastered in the system increases. It then becomes more and more difficult to imagine how a comprehensive theory is still possible. Perhaps in much higher degrees of abstraction. Perhaps only in the ecumenical conciliation of a \"postmodern\" discourse. One could then only sail around in the island world of discourse and, with the French philosopher Jean-Franfois Lyotard, view it from a ship."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ec74f1f66bfe30e1",
      "text": "[[Niklas Luhmann]] does not think that the notion of a unified, well-integrated theory should be abandoned so quickly. As far as the world is concerned, we may share the philosophers' resignation. But organizations are, after all, a well-contourable, well-defined set of facts. The book reissued here had attempted such an integration at the state of knowledge at that time. With this ambition of bringing together systems theory and decision theory and with the attempt to get from there both the informal sides within the systems and the deviations from ideas of rational decision making into view, the book has, as far as he can see, found no successor. This may account for its continued relevance and justify the new edition, for which the publisher is to be thanked. If one wanted to undertake a similar project at the present state of research, one would not only have to include the transdisciplinary efforts to develop a general theory of self-referential, \"autopoietic\" systems, but, in connection with this, one would also have to dissolve and recompose the concept of decision. It is difficult to estimate how one can get from there back to descriptions of the realities of everyday work in organizations that are relatively close to the milieu and recognizable for \"members\"."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0f49d0fec2ec5e38",
      "text": "Bielefeld, December 1994 – [[Niklas Luhmann]]"
