      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "07887497f097f327",
        "text": "When a book is reprinted unchanged thirty years after its first publication, this is likely to be an occasion to re-contextualize the text. This is especially true in a field that can be broadly described as empirical organization science, to include not only sociological organization research, but also social psychological and, in the broadest sense, \"behaviorist\" approaches of political, or economic, provenance. Undoubtedly, much has changed in this rapidly evolving field in thirty years. Even if one disregards the ongoing change of self-recommendation fashions in the management consulting literature, organizational science today is not the same as it was in 1964. But this need not mean that certain research perspectives have been refuted or otherwise rendered obsolete. For the most part, sciences do not develop according to the scientific-theoretical model of asserting, testing, and accepting or rejecting hypotheses. This would result in no history at all, but only a waste mountain of discarded attempts at knowledge. Rather, it seems to be the case that one works for a while with certain distinctions in order to work out what can be made visible with them, and when this begins to bore after some time, one moves on to other distinctions."
