        "text": "The American discussion, to which one could look back at the beginning of the 1960s, had enriched the schema formal / informal organization with certain added options, but also burdened it. Informal organization was mainly understood in terms of group psychology, i.e., as the spontaneous self-development of groups. This corresponded to widespread research interests in social psychology at that time. Furthermore, groups as bearers of informal organization had been observed and researched from the management's point of view. This brought into play another distinction that was only meaningful from this perspective, namely that of underperformance and overperformance. On the one hand, groups had to be expected to slow down performance to a level acceptable to them and to cooperate in covering up poor performance or mistakes; but on the other hand, given a good group climate, it was also possible to think in terms of additional performance, which could not have been ordered. Thus, one could hope and expect from the side of the researchers that the knowledge of the mechanisms of informal organization could be of help to the management in understanding the processes in the company and in the daily business of the management. Finally, since the famous Hawthorne experiments, the relevant research had taken place mainly in organizations of industrial production. There, groups were easy to discover because of the formal organization of work and their spatial (machine-related) coherence. But this also spared the question whether the extent to which formal organization leads to the formation of informal groups does not vary from type of organization to type of organization, so that the findings on informal organization can only be generalized to a very limited extent. During many years of work in public administration, [[Niklas Luhmann]] had encountered coalitions and networks of various kinds, but not groups in a sense that could be delimited on the basis of their self-understanding. Translated with www.DeepL.com/Translator (free version)"
