        "text": "Systems theory at that time was admittedly not yet in the form that could be observed twenty years later. Although the relationship between cybernetics and self-reference had already been lively discussed in the large Macy conferences of the 1950s, and although \"self-organization\" was an established topic around 1960, the export of systems theory to disciplines outside the core group was still based on relatively simple models – above all the stabilization model of negative feedback or homeostasis and the input/output model, which treated the transformation of inputs into outputs as a matter of a simple mathematical calculus or an appropriately constructed machine. The fact that this could not work for mathematical reasons as soon as outputs were reintroduced into the system as inputs, i.e. reflexive loops were formed, only became known later in wider circles."
