    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "0d498c2bd01cd3dd",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "0d498c2bd01cd3dd",
        "text": "Until well into the 1970s, therefore, systems theory was reproached for treating human things in the manner of machines and thus for placing them \"conservatively\" in the service of ruling classes. On the part of systems theory, there was at first only an attempt to provide within this theory for soothing distinctions, such as that of artificial and natural or that of mechanical and organic models, but the counter-models remained unclear and functioned only as placeholders for a complexity that could not yet be scientifically grasped. On these bases, the controversy could only be fought out ideologically, and eventually, after both sides had made their scent marks, lost its intellectual appeal. But this without the newer approaches to a theory of self-referential systems having been considered, let alone tried out as a theory of organization."
      },
      "after": "a3baa5a1265c61b4",
      "date": 1678725504466
