    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "11ac19e89ce585a5",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "11ac19e89ce585a5",
        "text": "In contrast, the view has become established, also and especially in organizational research, that systems cannot be regarded as artificial or natural wholes, but that the difference between system and environment must be assumed. In this sense, systems theory established the system/environment distinction as the guiding concept of organizational sociology. At first, the environment was treated as a turbulent, overly complex external world on which the organization was dependent, be it in its information, be it in its resources. The information/resource distinction, in turn, led to a bifurcation that brought into view either problems of uncertainty or problems of power in the sense of resource control. This so-called contingency theory was in turn criticized at the end of the 1970s with the accusation that it saw the environment of organizations as too unstructured, whereas in reality it was always a question of society, which had accepted certain cultural patterns and values and had thus always already limited its own complexity. So now the distinction system environment/society came into view, and contingency theory was supplemented by institutional theory, if not displaced from the prominent places of theory development. This corresponded to a conviction, spreading especially in business enterprises, that a company could not legitimize itself socially solely through its product, but that social factors and, most recently, ecological consequential problems of its production processes also played a role. For public administration, this corresponds to the insight that successful activity, especially in view of the expansion of tasks in the wake of the welfare state, cannot be legally enforced in many cases, but is dependent on the cooperation of those concerned. Of course, the old concept of institution can reflect this only very inadequately; but it at least responds to expanded conditions of acceptance of organizations in the society surrounding them. In these distinctions linked to distinctions, the insight gains of the old distinction of formal and informal organizations get out of sight without having been refuted or even devalued in any way. It is just that the spotlights of current interest tend to illuminate other areas, more the external relations of organizations. Translated with www.DeepL.com/Translator (free version)"
