      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "54f68c21e8e3f55b",
        "text": "However, it might become more difficult to still believe in the rationality of decisions under the conditions which are preferably of interest today, and thus we come across another theory development which has been influential especially since the 1970s. It lives from its opposition to the classical doctrine of optimal rationality, which for its part was based on the distinction between ends and means. The big names here are James March and Karl Weick. At the time of the publication of Functions and Consequences of Formal Organization, the trend was already visible, but had not attracted interest either in business administration (the exception being Horst AIbach) or in the sociology of organization. Herbert A. Simon had emphasized the limits of the information processing possibilities demanded by the principle of optimization, and had changed the theory of rational decision from an orientation towards the sole deciding entrepreneur to a theory of decisions of elaborating organizations. Following Simon, one already spoke of \"bounded rationality\". A two-stage model had been introduced, which worked with the assumption of decisions about decision premises. I was able to link to this state of affairs - especially with the thesis that the hiring and firing of members fixes, bundles and changes decision premises of the system. With this summary, it was possible to integrate systems theory, decision theory, and the theory of formal and informal organizations. A very consequential and successful book by Cyert and March on a behavioral theory of organizations had just been published. Nevertheless, the scope of this movement could not yet be estimated. Their concern was and is, as can be seen today, not only a critique of exaggerated rationality claims - as if management had to be brought back to the ground of empirical reality. Right down to the style of language, it is about the astonishment that it also works without rationality - and how it works."
      },
      "date": 1678726325915
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "54f68c21e8e3f55b",
