      "id": "590484d1c06013da",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "590484d1c06013da",
        "text": "When you tell history on the basis of distinctions, you don't tell it as it was meant to be told. Scientific discoveries become unilaterally flagged, for example, as informal organization or not-so-rational decision-making. Reconstructing distinctions neutralizes, in a sense, the joys of discovery and the punctuations at which discontinuities make themselves felt. One must abandon the hope of telling the history of science according to the \"A causes B\" causal model. Rather, it is a history of continuous discontinuity, a history of \"reaction to ...,\" a self-motivating history. But if one wants to tell history not as a history of facts, but as a history of observations, it must be noted that any designation of something thereby determined requires the distinction from something else - first, of course, the distinction from \"everything else,\" especially in the history of science, but also the distinction from the hitherto usual.\n"
      },
      "after": "ddfed6edc7a218e5",
