    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "ec74f1f66bfe30e1",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "ec74f1f66bfe30e1",
        "text": "[[Niklas Luhmann]] does not think that the notion of a unified, well-integrated theory should be abandoned so quickly. As far as the world is concerned, we may share the philosophers' resignation. But organizations are, after all, a well-contourable, well-defined set of facts. The book reissued here had attempted such an integration at the state of knowledge at that time. With this ambition of bringing together systems theory and decision theory and with the attempt to get from there both the informal sides within the systems and the deviations from ideas of rational decision making into view, the book has, as far as I can see, found no successor. This may account for its continued relevance and justify the new edition, for which the publisher is to be thanked. If one wanted to undertake a similar project at the present state of research, one would not only have to include the transdisciplinary efforts to develop a general theory of self-referential, \"autopoietic\" systems, but, in connection with this, one would also have to dissolve and recompose the concept of decision. It is difficult to estimate how one can get from there back to descriptions of the realities of everyday work in organizations that are relatively close to the milieu and recognizable for \"members\"."
