        "text": "This was also a motive not to give up the insights into a difference between formal and informal organization, but to complement and relativize them by another distinction, and for this, based on the state of research at that time, above all the distinction between system and environment came into consideration. Roughly speaking, it offered the possibility of tracing the difference between formal and informal organization back to the differentiation of a social system \"organization\"; for one could imagine that the difference thus created imposed problems on the differentiated system which could not be solved by the means of formal organization alone, i.e. not by a departmental division and a hierarchy which concentrated external contacts (or at least: their regulation) at the top of the system if possible. Above all, the concrete work motivation of the members, but also the inconspicuous and relatively smooth solution of the problems, which today [[Transaction Cost Analysis]] discusses, can hardly be sufficiently guaranteed by formal regulations. "
